indoorPOIs.infoHtml: In the heart of La Marsa, a small town in the northern suburbs of Tunis, the Saf Saf café attracts a lot of people, summer and winter. This old 18th century café has an old well dating back to even older times. It is covered with zellig tiles: Andalusian earthenware. A beautiful noria, a bucket wheel, is used to raise the water from the well thanks to a camel that turns tirelessly. The great painters of the 1950s, Yahya Turki, Noureddine Khayachi and Jellal Ben Abdallah frequented the Saf saf and have represented it in their paintings. Great Tunisian singers like Naama and Ali Riahi celebrated it in their songs. It has remained very popular and very popular with Tunisians and now also with tourists.
Try good steaks, pasta and pizza to form your opinion about this restaurant. Many visitors find the staff hospitable. Mamalik is remarkable for its fine service

This café is a tribute to the great Egyptian singer, musician and actress Oum Kalthoum, nicknamed the Star of the East (1898-1975). Her songs are heard and appreciated all over the Arab world, especially in Tunisia, a country she visited in May 1968, a year after the Egyptian army was defeated in the 1967 war.

A beautiful staircase distinguishes this place of relaxation in two parts. Below, the Oum Kalthoum café is named after the one found in Cairo, a veritable temple in memory of this great Egyptian singer. Its followers can hear there, from morning to evening, the voice of the eternal "young lady". Here the walls are decorated with his engraved portrait and excerpts from his songs.
